{\f2\fs18 // Before:\line const config: any = \{\line   audio_url: uploadUrl,\line   speaker_labels: true,\line   sentiment_analysis: true,\line   ...\line \};\line\line // After:\line const config: any = \{\line   audio_url: uploadUrl,\line   speech_model: 'universal-3-pro',\line   speaker_labels: true,\line   sentiment_analysis: true,\line   ...\line \};}
\par\par

{\f0\fs24 9.2 Why}
\par\par
{\f1\fs22 The AssemblyAI API began requiring an explicit }{\f2\fs20 speech_model}{\f1\fs22  value. Without it, the API returned the validation error }{\f3\fs22 "speech_models" must be a non-empty list}{\f1\fs22 , causing diarization to fail for every transcription. This meant no speaker identification, no enriched data (word-level confidence, sentiment, entities), and the Claude enriched refinement path was unavailable \u8212 forcing the pipeline to use the inferior standard refinement path with heuristic speaker assignment.}
\par\par

{\f0\fs18 ________________________________________________________________________________}
\par\par

{\f0\fs32 10. FIX: SPEAKER REFINEMENT FOR LARGE TRANSCRIPTS (TASK #21)}
\par\par
{\f1\fs22\cf6 Commits: 1fab0d1, d15efcf, 84d4791, cd11447\line Date: March 22, 2026 21:04\u821322:07\line File: }{\f2\fs20\cf6 server/speakerRefinement.ts}{\f1\fs22\cf6  (+107 lines, -14 lines)}
\par\par

{\f0\fs24 10.1 What Was Changed}
\par\par
{\f1\fs22 Five interconnected changes to fix Claude Opus 4 speaker refinement for transcripts exceeding 350 segments:}
\par\par

{\f0\fs22 10.1.1 Batch Size Reduction}
\par
{\f2\fs18 SINGLE_CALL_LIMIT: 800 -> 350\line BATCH_SIZE:        700 -> 200}
\par\par
{\f1\fs22 Previously, transcripts up to 800 segments were sent to Claude in a single API call. This frequently exceeded Claude's effective output capacity, causing truncated JSON responses that lost the end of the transcript. Lowered to 350 for single calls and 200 per batch for large transcripts. These numbers ensure Claude's response fits within }{\f2\fs20 max_tokens}{\f1\fs22  limits.}
\par\par

{\f0\fs22 10.1.2 Max Tokens Increase}
\par
{\f2\fs18 max_tokens formula: min(32000, max(8192, segments * 80 + 2000))\line                                   was: segments * 40 + 2000}
\par\par
{\f1\fs22 Doubled the per-segment token allocation from 40 to 80. For a 200-segment batch, this produces }{\f2\fs20 max_tokens = 18,000}{\f1\fs22  (previously 10,000). This accounts for Claude's verbose JSON output format which includes the "i" index field, quoted labels, quoted text, and whitespace.}
\par\par

{\f0\fs22 10.1.3 Segment Index Anchoring}
\par
{\f1\fs22 Each segment sent to Claude now includes an }{\f2\fs20 "i"}{\f1\fs22  (index) field:}
\par
{\f2\fs18 // Segment data sent to Claude:\line [\{"i": 0, "s": "Speaker 1", "t": "This begins the video deposition..."\},\line  \{"i": 1, "s": "Speaker 1", "t": "Please state your name."\},\line  ...]}
\par\par
{\f1\fs22 The system prompt was updated to instruct Claude to echo the }{\f2\fs20 "i"}{\f1\fs22  index in each output segment, creating a 1:1 mapping between input and output that survives segment count mismatches. The prompt also includes a CRITICAL instruction: }{\f3\fs22 "The array length MUST EXACTLY equal the number of input segments \u8212 no more, no fewer."}
\par\par
{\f1\fs22 The }{\f2\fs20 ParsedSegment}{\f1\fs22  interface was updated:}
\par
{\f2\fs18 // Before:\line interface ParsedSegment \{ label: string; text: string; \}\line\line // After:\line interface ParsedSegment \{ i?: number; label: string; text: string; \}}
\par\par

{\f0\fs22 10.1.4 Index-Based Mismatch Recovery}
\par
{\f1\fs22 The }{\f2\fs20 parseResponse()}{\f1\fs22  function was rewritten with tiered recovery for when Claude returns the wrong number of segments:}
\par\par
{\f2\fs18 Exact match or within 10%: accept directly (existing behavior)\line\line Oversized (Claude returned MORE segments than expected):\line   1. Build a Map<index, segment> from the "i" field of each response segment\line   2. If >= 80% of expected indices are present: reconstruct by index\line      (missing indices get empty label/text)\line   3. If < 80%: fall back to identifications map\line\line Undersized (Claude returned FEWER segments than expected):\line   1. If >= 50% present: pad with empty segments\line   2. If < 50%: fall back to identifications map\line\line All paths: identifications map (\{"Speaker 1": "Officer Ken"\}) is always\line extracted and can be applied as a last resort even if no per-segment data\line is usable.}
\par\par

{\f0\fs22 10.1.5 Truncated JSON Repair}
\par
{\f1\fs22 A new }{\f2\fs20 tryRepairTruncatedJson()}{\f1\fs22  function handles Claude responses that are cut off mid-JSON due to token limits:}
\par\par
{\f2\fs18 1. Find the "segments" key in the JSON string\line 2. Find the last complete segment object boundary (pattern: \},\{)\line 3. Truncate at that point\line 4. Count unclosed brackets and braces\line 5. Append the necessary closing characters\line 6. Return the repaired JSON string for re-parsing\line\line Example: If Claude's response ends mid-segment at token limit:\line   \{"segments": [\{"i":0, "label":"Ken", "text":"Hello"\}, \{"i":1, "label":"R\line   -> Repaired to:\line   \{"segments": [\{"i":0, "label":"Ken", "text":"Hello"\}]\}}
\par\par

{\f0\fs18 ________________________________________________________________________________}
\par\par

{\f0\fs32 11. FIX: WHISPER HALLUCINATION DETECTION}
\par\par
{\f1\fs22\cf6 Commit: 9f956ab\line Date: March 22, 2026 22:10\line File: }{\f2\fs20\cf6 server/transcription.ts}{\f1\fs22\cf6  (+30 lines, -6 lines)}
\par\par

{\f0\fs24 11.1 What Was Changed}
\par\par
{\f1\fs22 The }{\f2\fs20 removeHallucinatedSegments()}{\f1\fs22  function in }{\f2\fs20 server/transcription.ts}{\f1\fs22  was enhanced with a new detection method and relaxed tolerances.}
\par\par

{\f0\fs22 11.1.1 Dominant Hallucination Detection (NEW)}
\par
{\f1\fs22 Before the existing run-based detection, a new pre-scan counts how often each short phrase (\u8804 3 words) appears across ALL segments:}
\par\par
{\f2\fs18 const textCounts = new Map<string, number>();\line for (const seg of segments) \{\line   const t = seg.text.trim().toLowerCase();\line   const wc = t.split(/\\s+/).length;\line   if (wc <= 3) textCounts.set(t, (textCounts.get(t) || 0) + 1);\line \}\line\line Trigger condition: count >= 50% of total segments AND count >= 10\line Action: Remove ALL instances (not just consecutive runs)}
\par\par
{\f1\fs22 This catches the pattern seen in the body cam hallucination: 403 out of 407 segments were "Mm-hmm." (99%). The previous run-based detector missed this because occasional "Ah." and "hrnm" segments broke the consecutive runs, and some sub-runs had timing deviation beyond the old 0.5-second tolerance.}
\par\par

{\f0\fs22 11.1.2 Spacing Tolerance Increase}
\par
{\f2\fs18 // Run-based uniform spacing check:\line maxDeviation <= 0.5  ->  maxDeviation <= 1.5}
\par\par
{\f1\fs22 The run-based detector requires uniform time spacing between repeated segments to identify hallucinations. Whisper's timestamp jitter on long recordings (35+ minutes) can exceed 0.5 seconds, causing legitimate hallucination runs to be missed. Increased to 1.5 seconds.}
\par\par

{\f0\fs22 11.1.3 Empty Transcript Handling}
\par
{\f1\fs22 If the dominant hallucination filter removes ALL segments (i.e., the entire transcript is hallucinated), the function now returns an empty array with a log message instead of proceeding to the run-based detector with an empty array (which would have thrown an error).}
\par\par

{\f0\fs24 11.2 Why}
\par\par
{\f1\fs22 A body cam recording (Axon Body 3, 2022-01-01, ~35 minutes) produced 407 segments from Whisper, of which 403 were "Mm-hmm.", 3 were "hrnm", and 1 was "Ah." \u8212 pure hallucination with no actual speech content. This garbage reached Claude refinement, wasting API cost and producing a useless transcript. The same file had been successfully transcribed 7 days earlier with 364 real segments, indicating non-deterministic Whisper behavior on noisy audio.}
\par\par

